{
  "doc_id": "45311",
  "text": "After the initial discovery of the ectABC gene cluster for the synthesis of ectoine in Marinococcus halophilus [CITATION_1] , transcriptional profiling of the corresponding genes in several Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria showed that they were transcribed as operons inducible by osmotic or temperature stress [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In some ectoine producers, the ectABC genes are expressed from a single promoter [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , whereas in others a more complex pattern of regulation of this gene cluster has been reported [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Evidence for the presence of a putatively nitrogen-responsive Sig-54 type promoter driving the separate expression of ectC has been presented in the case of H. elongata [CITATION_13] .",
